text: (upbeat music)
- My name is Jennie Seo.

I've been with AWS for
about one and a half years.
What I do is I'm a front end engineer.

So I basically work on
the user interface aspect
of our web application.
I'm originally from Canada,
from Winnipeg and I grew up there.

Didn't really think of
moving to the States
until this job opportunity came.

I've always really
liked to do video games,

and actually, I didn't go
into video games right away.

I started off university
being an accountant,
thinking I'd become a business major,
and I figured out it wasn't for me.
So I went back to school,

and I stumbled upon a
computer science course,
and absolutely loved it,

and did some internships
in video games and thought,
"Wow, this is a great place to be".

And you know how your
parents are always like,

"Stop playing video games,
it'll ruin your brains.

What are you gonna do when
you're older, play video games?"
And I'm like, "Mom, I still do that".
So it's been great,
and Amazon has this amazing opportunity
to work for game tech.
So I hopped on the bandwagon,
and moved myself here to Seattle.
(upbeat music)
I helped create an application

for creating backend
tools for video games.
Our audience is video game developers,
and we want those video game developers

to focus of the most important
aspects of their game,
like their story, et cetera,
and we work on the back end

so they can pick and choose
whatever they want from us,
and focus on what's important to them.
(upbeat music)
We provide those backend features
that a lot of video games have in common.
You can, kind of, pick and choose
what you need for your particular game,
and then just integrate it with your game.

So you can, kind of, get the
ball rolling much faster,

whether you're a big studio
or an indie developer.
(upbeat music)

Video games are basically a
different way of storytelling,

and I think that's the thing
that gets me up in the morning,

knowing that I'm helping
people tell their stories,

helping people be passionate
about their creative outcome.
(upbeat music)
